      <h3>Food Security National Policy</h3>

      <p>Malaysia's government prioritizes food security through:
      <br>• Cold storage capacity expansion: +30% by 2030
      <br>• Cold chain logistics infrastructure development
      <br>• Grants for cold storage and transport equipment (up to RM500,000 per facility)
      <br>• Tax incentives for food logistics investment</p>

      <h3>E-Commerce Food Delivery Revolution</h3>

      <p>Online grocery and food delivery grew 35% in 2024:
      <br>• Frozen food delivery services expanding nationwide
      <br>• Last-mile cold chain delivery in urban areas
      <br>• Demand for temperature-controlled transport 20-25% growth annually</p>

      <h3>Export Market Expansion</h3>

      <p>Malaysia frozen food exports accelerating:
      <br>• Seafood exports: +15% annually (require cold transport to airports/seaports)
      <br>• Fruits (durian, tropical fruits): Cold chain for export quality maintenance
      <br>• Halal frozen foods: Middle East markets growing demand</p>

      <h2>Cold Chain Lorry vs Standard Lorry: Key Differences</h2>

      <h3>Refrigeration System</h3>

      <p><strong>Cold Chain Lorry Features:</strong>
      <br>• Integrated refrigeration unit (Thermo King, Carrier, etc.)
      <br>• Temperature control: -25°C to +15°C range
      <br>• Multiple temperature zones (frozen, chilled, ambient in same lorry)
      <br>• Real-time temperature monitoring and recording</p>

      <h3>Insulation and Construction</h3>

      <p><strong>Specialized Build:</strong>
      <br>• Enhanced insulation (50-100mm polyurethane foam walls)
      <br>• Seamless body construction (no thermal bridges)
      <br>• Non-porous floors (sanitary for food transport)
      <br>• Waterproof interior (easy cleaning and sanitation)</p>

      <h3>Power Systems</h3>

      <p><strong>Continuous Cooling Requirements:</strong>
      <br>• Engine-driven refrigeration (runs while lorry operates)
      <br>• Standby generator (electric plug-in at delivery locations)
      <br>• Battery backup system (maintains cooling during stops)</p>

      <h2>The Cost Factor: Cold Chain Lorry Pricing</h2>

      <h3>Equipment Cost Comparison</h3>

      <p><strong>Standard 5-Ton Lorry (Box Body):</strong> RM180,000 - RM220,000
      <br><strong>Standard 10-Ton Lorry (Box Body):</strong> RM280,000 - RM350,000
      <br><strong>Cold Chain 5-Ton Lorry (Refrigerated):</strong> RM280,000 - RM380,000
      <br><strong>Cold Chain 10-Ton Lorry (Refrigerated):</strong> RM420,000 - RM550,000</p>

      <p><strong>Cost Premium:</strong> 50-80% more than standard lorries</p>

      <h3>Why the Higher Cost?</h3>

      <p>Specialized components add significant cost:
      <br>• Refrigeration unit: RM50,000-RM80,000
      <br>• Insulated body construction: RM30,000-RM50,000 additional
      <br>• Temperature monitoring systems: RM5,000-RM15,000
      <br>• Backup power systems: RM8,000-RM15,000
      <br>• Specialized manufacturing and certification: RM5,000-RM10,000</p>

      <h2>ROI Analysis: Cold Chain Premium Justification</h2>

      <h3>Scenario: 5-Ton Lorry Decision</h3>

      <p><strong>Option A: Standard Lorry for Mixed Cargo</strong>
      <br>• Revenue: RM15,000 monthly (general cargo, some food)
      <br>• Limitation: Cannot transport frozen food (food safety compliance)
      <br>• Competition: High (many standard lorries available)
      <br><strong>Potential Monthly Revenue:</strong> RM15,000-RM18,000</p>

      <p><strong>Option B: Cold Chain Lorry for Food Transport</strong>
      <br>• Revenue: RM25,000 monthly (dedicated frozen food transport)
      <br>• Advantage: Premium pricing for temperature-controlled service
      <br>• Market: Growing demand, limited competition
      <br><strong>Potential Monthly Revenue:</strong> RM25,000-RM32,000</p>

      <p><strong>5-Year Analysis:</strong>
      <br>• Additional revenue with cold chain: RM7,000-RM14,000/month
      <br>• Annual additional revenue: RM84,000-RM168,000
      <br>• 5-Year additional revenue: RM420,000-RM840,000</p>

      <p><strong>Equipment Cost Difference:</strong>
